y lists in the 2019 European Parliament election in the Netherlands#PVV (Party for Freedom)|List]]'''\n| 194,178\n| 3.53 (#10)\n| {{Composition bar|1|29|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| 1 {{increase}}\n| <ref name=\"BrexitVVDPVVFVD\">{{cite news|title=Extra zetel Europees Parlement naar PVV|url=https://www.nu.nl/europese-verkiezingen-2019/5910381/extra-zetel-na-brexit-gaat-niet-naar-groenlinks-maar-naar-forum.html|publisher=Nu.nl|language=nl-NL|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Representation==\n===Members of the House of Representatives===\nThe twenty members (fourteen men, six women) of the [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]] for the Party for Freedom are:<ref>\"[https://www.houseofrepresentatives.nl/parliamentary-parties/party-for-freedom Party for Freedom]\", ''[[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]]''. Retrieved 24 March 2017.</ref>\n{{div col}}\n* '''[[Geert Wilders]]''', [[parliamentary leader]]\n* [[Roy van Aalst]]\n* [[Fleur Agema]]\n* [[Harm Beertema]]\n* [[Martin Bosma]]\n* [[Teun van Dijck]]\n* [[Sietse Fritsma]]\n* [[Karen Gerbrands]]\n* [[Machiel de Graaf]]\n* [[Dion Graus]]\n* [[Lilian Helder]]\n* [[L\u00e9on de Jong]]\n* [[Alexander Kops]]\n* [[Barry Madlener]]\n* [[Vicky Maeijer]]\n* [[Gidi Markuszower]]\n* [[Edgar Mulder]]\n* [[Gabri\u00eblle Popken]]\n* [[Raymond de Roon]]\n* [[Danai van Weerdenburg]]\n{{Col div end}}\n\n===Members of the Senate===\nThe nine members (eight men, one woman) of the [[Senate (Netherlands)|Senate]] for the Party for Freedom are:<ref>\"[https://www.eerstekamer.nl/fractie/partij_voor_de_vrijheid PVV-fractie]\" (in Dutch), ''[[Senate (Netherlands)|Senate]]''. Retrieved 28 February 2018.</ref>\n* '''[[Marjolein Faber]]''', [[parliamentary leader]]\n* [[Martin van Beek]]\n* [[Ren\u00e9 Dercksen]]\n* [[Peter van Dijk]]\n* [[Alexander van Hattem]]\n* [[Ton van Kesteren]]\n* [[Kees Kok]]\n* [[Dannij van der Sluijs]]\n* [[Gom van Strien]]\n\n===Members of the European Parliament===\n{{further|2019 European Parliament election in the Netherlands}}\n{{see also|List of Party for Freedom Members of the European Parliament}}\n{{see also|Party lists in the 2019 European Parliament election in the Netherlands#PVV (Party for Freedom)}}\nThe PVV lost all it seats in the 2019 European Parliament election. The party is however due to have an MEP appointed in the wake of the re-allocation of UK seats after Brexit<br />\n0 Seats:\n\n==See also==<!-- PLEASE RESPECT ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\n{{Portal|Conservatism}}\n* [[Cultural conservatism]]\n* [[Criticism of Islam]]\n* [[Criticism of Islamism]]\n* [[Criticism of multiculturalism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n*{{Official website|https://www.pvv.nl/}} (in Dutch)\n{{Dutch Political Parties}}\n{{Geert Wilders}}\n{{Movement for a Europe of Nations and Freedom}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Party For Freedom}}\n[[Category:Party for Freedom| ]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Geert Wilders]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Political parties in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Anti-Islam political parties]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populist parties]]\n[[Category:Member parties of the Identity and Democracy Party]]\n", "name_user": "Peipsi-Pihkva", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eImmigration:East Europeans", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Party_for_Freedom"}
{"title_page": "Boo McLee", "text_new": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name                =Kevin \"Boo\" McLee\n|image               =\n|caption             =\n|status              =\n|position     =Linebacker\n|number              =\n|college             =[[West Virginia University|West Virginia]]\n|birth_date          ={{birth date|1983|11|24}}\n|birth_place         =[[Caddo Parish]] [[Shreveport, Louisiana]]\n|death_date          ={{death date and age|2020|4|12|1983|11|24}}\n|death_place        =[[Uniontown, Pennsylvania]] \n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 1\n|weight_lbs = 244\n|undraftedyear       =2007\n|pastteams           =\n* [[2007 St. Louis Rams season|St. Louis Rams]] ({{NFL Year|2007}})*\n* [[Calgary Stampeders]] ({{CFL Year|2008}})*\n* [[Wheeling Wildcats]] ({{CIFL Year|2009}})\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|highlights          =\n* [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]] All-[[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]] First-team\n* 2005 All-[[Eastern College Athletic Conference|ECAC]]\n|afl                 =11172\n}}\n'''Kevin '''\"'''Boo'''\"''' McLee Jr.'''<ref name=Kevin>{{cite web |url=http://www.stlouisrams.com/article/61187/ |accessdate=2007-11-16 |title=Rams Add 19 Undrafted Rookies |publisher=StLouisRams.com |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071018001859/http://stlouisrams.com/article/61187/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-10-18}}</ref> (November 24, 1983 \u2013 April 12, 2020<ref>[https://www.timeswv.com/sports/former-wvu-linebacker-mclee-dies-at-age-36/article_f69c9368-7d16-11ea-936f-0f8c7c757541.html Former WVU linebacker McLee dies at age 36]</ref> ) was an [[American football]] [[linebacker]]. He played collegiately at [[West Virginia University]].\n\nMcLee played for the [[St. Louis Rams]] of the NFL and the [[Calgary Stampeders]] of the CFL.\n\n==College career==\nDuring high school in Uniontown, PA (suburban Pittsburgh), McLee rushed for 1,637 yards and led the team in [[Tackle (football move)|tackles]]. McLee also [[Varsity letter|lettered]] in [[basketball]] and [[Track and field|track]].\n\nFollowing his uncle Billy and cousin Reggie McLee's footsteps, McLee attended [[West Virginia University]]. He was interested in [[Michigan State]] and [[University of Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh]], but neither one gave him offers. McLee redshirted his 2002 freshman year, learning the complex 3-3-5 defensive scheme, but was rookie of the week in practice during the game week against the [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami Hurricanes]].\n\n===Freshman (2002)===\nIn [[2002 NCAA Division I-A football season|2002]], McLee red-shirted his true freshman season.\n\n===Freshman (2003)===\nIn [[2003 NCAA Division I-A football season|2003]], McLee got more playing time with the graduation of [[Grant Wiley]], 2002's starting linebacker. Behind linebacker Scott Gyorko, McLee totaled 46 tackles for the year and three sacks. McLee recorded two tackles against [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin]], three tackles and a sack in the game against the [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]], and six tackles, a sack, and a fumble recovery against the [[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland]]. McLee also forced fumble against Miami and [[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech]]. In the [[Gator Bowl]], McLee recorded six tackles.\n\n===Sophomore (2004)===\nIn [[2004 NCAA Division I-A football season|2004]], McLee played on the Mountaineer team that was expected to be National Championship contenders with [[Rasheed Marshall]], [[Adam Jones (American football)|Adam \"Pacman\" Jones]], [[Chris Henry (wide receiver)|Chris Henry]], and [[Kay-Jay Harris]]. Although the Mountaineers ended 8-4, McLee had a good season. McLee shared time with fellow junior Jeff Noechel, but recorded 44 tackles on the year. In an overtime win against Maryland, McLee recorded six tackles and forced a fumble. Against Virginia Tech, McLee led the team with 11 tackles and recorded a 10-yard sack against [[Boston College Eagles football|Boston College]]. McLee had a team-best eight tackles in the [[Gator Bowl]] loss to [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]].\n\n===Junior (2005)===\nIn [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]], McLee teamed up with a strong defense of [[Mike Lorello]] and [[Jahmile Addae]] at safeties. McLee earned 2005 first-team All-[[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]] honors, [[ESPN]] All-Conference honors, and All-[[Eastern College Athletic Conference|ECAC]] honors as the starter. McLee recorded 78 tackles, which was second-best on the team. McLee had a team-high six tackles at [[Syracuse Orange#Football history|Syracuse]] for the season-opener, a team-best 11 tackles in the [[East Carolina Pirates football|East Carolina]] win, team-best nine tackles and a sack of [[Marcus Vick]] against Virginia Tech, 10 tackles and two pass break-ups in overtime win against the [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]], 30-yard interception against [[Connecticut Huskies#Football|UConn]], and was the leading tackler with 11 tackles against Pitt. McLee won Girdiron Gladiator Award from the West Virginia coaches and was the Big East player of the week against Cincinnati. He was also named MVP on defense against Syracuse, Virginia Tech, Cincinnati, and Pitt.\n\n===Senior (2006)===\nIn [[2006 NCAA Division I-A football season|2006]], McLee finally started the whole season. He finished the season with 79 tackles but no sacks. McLee had his second career interception against Connecticut, which he returned for 10 yards. McLee had 9 tackles against [[Marshall University#Athletics|Marshall]], six tackles against Maryland, six against Syracuse, six against Connecticut, six against Cincinnati, and eight tackles in the overtime win against [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]]. McLee finished the season on the [[Butkus Award]] list and traveled to the [[Senior Bowl]].<ref>[http://www.nfl-draft-site.com/2007/01/official-senior-bowl-roster.html The NFL Draft Site: Official Senior Bowl Roster]</ref> In his final game as a Mountaineer, McLee totaled three tackles against [[2006 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football team|Georgia Tech]] in the [[Gator Bowl]].\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Pre-Draft===\nDuring the Senior Bowl, McLee was reported to be \"looking quick\". ESPN ranked McLee as the #14 inside linebacker in the class, out of the 29-ranked inside linebacker prospects. His toughness was praised, while his discipline and learning of schemes were issues. McLee played all three linebacking positions in college, which NFL scouts praised.\n\n===NFL Draft===\nMcLee went undrafted in the [[2007 NFL Draft]]. A day later, McLee signed with the [[St. Louis Rams]], who did not take any linebackers in the draft, as an undrafted free agent. \"It's a slap in the face,\" McLee said. \"Not one of us was drafted. It's very disappointing. We're going to show the league that we can play... They're going to notice us.\"\n\nOn July 18, 2007, McLee's father, Kevin McLee Sr.,<ref name=Kevin /> who was a running back at [[University of Georgia|Georgia]], and former [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Tampa Bay Buccaneer]]<ref name=\"Kevin \"/> died at the age of 52.<ref name=\"McLee Sr.\">{{cite web | url = http://pittsburghlive.com/x/tribunereview/news/fayette/s_517790.html | accessdate = 2008-04-01 | title = Ex-Georgia RB, Uniontown native McLee dies at 52 - Tribune-Review | publisher = PittsburghLIVE.com }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2007, McLee was charged with intent to deliver [[cocaine]] and [[marijuana]] and several traffic violations.<ref>[http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/dailycourier/news/s_552637.html Waives hearing - PittsburghLIVE.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The charges were dropped on February 12, 2008. The charges where however were refiled on February 18.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/dailycourier/news/s_552996.html# |title=Sale of tiger skin |access-date=2008-04-01 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20081016144529/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/dailycourier/news/s_552996.html# |archive-date=2008-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===CFL===\nFollowing being cut by the St. Louis Rams, McLee was signed by the Calgary Stampeders of the [[Canadian Football League]] to a one-year deal. He reported that the [[Green Bay Packers]] were interested in him after his season with Calgary. McLee was later released by Calgary.\n\n===AFL===\nIn 2008, he played in the [[af2]] (a sort of \"farm league\" for the [[Arena Football League]]) with the [[Iowa Barnstormers]] and the [[Green Bay Blizzard]].<ref name=\"'Eers in Pros Profile\">[http://eersinpros.blogspot.com/search/label/Boo%20Mclee 'Eers in Pros Profile]</ref>\n\n===UNGL===\nMclee was drafted into the newly created [[United National Gridiron League]] by [[Team Louisiana]]<ref name=\"'Eers in Pros Profile\"/>\n\n==Personal==\nIn 2016, McLee was charged in a string of bank robberies in [[Pittsburgh]] and [[Crafton, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2016/08/29/former-mountaineers-linebacker-charged-in-string-of-bank-robberies/|title=Former Mountaineers linebacker charged in string of bank robberies|website=[[West Virginia MetroNews]]|date=August 29, 2016|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He pleaded guilty in 2019.<ref name=\"TimesWV\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timeswv.com/sports/former-wvu-linebacker-mclee-dies-at-age-36/article_f69c9368-7d16-11ea-936f-0f8c7c757541.html|title=Former WVU linebacker McLee dies at age 36|first=Bob|last=Hertzel|website=[[Times West Virginian]]|date=April 12, 2020|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMcLee died on April 12, 2020.<ref name=\"TimesWV\"/>\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.msnsportsnet.com/page.cfm?story=8119 Letting It Rip By John Antonik for MSNsportsNET.com August 18, 2005]\n* [http://sports.aol.com/fanhouse/2007/04/30/west-virginia-shut-out-in-the-2007-draft/ West Virginia Shut Out in the 2007 Draft]\n* [http://www.heraldstandard.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=18262714&BRD=2280&PAG=461&dept_id=468632&rfi=6 The Herald Standard - McLee prepared to make that big step to the NFL]\n* [http://www.heraldstandard.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=18278850&BRD=2280&PAG=461&dept_id=468632&rfi=6 The Herald Standard - McLee signed as free agent by Rams]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://insider.espn.go.com/nfldraft/draft/tracker/player?id=10941 Draft tracker] on [[ESPN.com]]\n* [http://eersinpros.blogspot.com/search/label/Boo%20Mclee 'Eers in Pros Profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title=WVU Starting Middle Linebacker| before=[[Grant Wiley]] | after=[[Reed Williams]]|years=2003 - 2006}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McLee, Boo}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Shreveport, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:People from Uniontown, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:West Virginia Mountaineers football players]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Rams players]]\n[[Category:Wheeling Wildcats players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name                =Kevin \"Boo\" McLee\n|image               =\n|caption             =\n|status              =\n|position     =Linebacker\n|number              =\n|college             =[[West Virginia University|West Virginia]]\n|birth_date          ={{birth date|1983|11|24}}\n|birth_place         =[[Caddo Parish]] [[Shreveport, Louisiana]]\n|death_date          ={{death date and age|2020|4|12|1983|11|24}}\n|death_place        =[[Uniontown, Pennsylvania]] \n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 1\n|weight_lbs = 244\n|undraftedyear       =2007\n|pastteams           =\n* [[2007 St. Louis Rams season|St. Louis Rams]] ({{NFL Year|2007}})*\n* [[Calgary Stampeders]] ({{CFL Year|2008}})*\n* [[Wheeling Wildcats]] ({{CIFL Year|2009}})\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|highlights          =\n* [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]] All-[[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]] First-team\n* 2005 All-[[Eastern College Athletic Conference|ECAC]]\n|afl                 =11172\n}}\n'''Kevin '''\"'''Boo'''\"''' McLee Jr.'''<ref name=Kevin>{{cite web |url=http://www.stlouisrams.com/article/61187/ |accessdate=2007-11-16 |title=Rams Add 19 Undrafted Rookies |publisher=StLouisRams.com |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071018001859/http://stlouisrams.com/article/61187/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-10-18}}</ref> (November 24, 1983 \u2013 April 12, 2020<ref>[https://www.timeswv.com/sports/former-wvu-linebacker-mclee-dies-at-age-36/article_f69c9368-7d16-11ea-936f-0f8c7c757541.html Former WVU linebacker McLee dies at age 36]</ref> ) was an [[American football]] [[linebacker]]. He played collegiately at [[West Virginia University]].\n\nMcLee played for the [[St. Louis Rams]] of the NFL and the [[Calgary Stampeders]] of the CFL.\n\n==College career==\nDuring high school in Uniontown, PA (suburban Pittsburgh), McLee rushed for 1,637 yards and led the team in [[Tackle (football move)|tackles]]. McLee also [[Varsity letter|lettered]] in [[basketball]] and [[Track and field|track]].\n\nFollowing his uncle Billy and cousin Reggie McLee's footsteps, McLee attended [[West Virginia University]]. He was interested in [[Michigan State]] and [[University of Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh]], but neither one gave him offers. McLee redshirted his 2002 freshman year, learning the complex 3-3-5 defensive scheme, but was rookie of the week in practice during the game week against the [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami Hurricanes]].\n\n===Freshman (2002)===\nIn [[2002 NCAA Division I-A football season|2002]], McLee red-shirted his true freshman season.\n\n===Freshman (2003)===\nIn [[2003 NCAA Division I-A football season|2003]], McLee got more playing time with the graduation of [[Grant Wiley]], 2002's starting linebacker. Behind linebacker Scott Gyorko, McLee totaled 46 tackles for the year and three sacks. McLee recorded two tackles against [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin]], three tackles and a sack in the game against the [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]], and six tackles, a sack, and a fumble recovery against the [[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland]]. McLee also forced fumble against Miami and [[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech]]. In the [[Gator Bowl]], McLee recorded six tackles.\n\n===Sophomore (2004)===\nIn [[2004 NCAA Division I-A football season|2004]], McLee played on the Mountaineer team that was expected to be National Championship contenders with [[Rasheed Marshall]], [[Adam Jones (American football)|Adam \"Pacman\" Jones]], [[Chris Henry (wide receiver)|Chris Henry]], and [[Kay-Jay Harris]]. Although the Mountaineers ended 8-4, McLee had a good season. McLee shared time with fellow junior Jeff Noechel, but recorded 44 tackles on the year. In an overtime win against Maryland, McLee recorded six tackles and forced a fumble. Against Virginia Tech, McLee led the team with 11 tackles and recorded a 10-yard sack against [[Boston College Eagles football|Boston College]]. McLee had a team-best eight tackles in the [[Gator Bowl]] loss to [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]].\n\n===Junior (2005)===\nIn [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]], McLee teamed up with a strong defense of [[Mike Lorello]] and [[Jahmile Addae]] at safeties. McLee earned 2005 first-team All-[[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]] honors, [[ESPN]] All-Conference honors, and All-[[Eastern College Athletic Conference|ECAC]] honors as the starter. McLee recorded 78 tackles, which was second-best on the team. McLee had a team-high six tackles at [[Syracuse Orange#Football history|Syracuse]] for the season-opener, a team-best 11 tackles in the [[East Carolina Pirates football|East Carolina]] win, team-best nine tackles and a sack of [[Marcus Vick]] against Virginia Tech, 10 tackles and two pass break-ups in overtime win against the [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]], 30-yard interception against [[Connecticut Huskies#Football|UConn]], and was the leading tackler with 11 tackles against Pitt. McLee won Girdiron Gladiator Award from the West Virginia coaches and was the Big East player of the week against Cincinnati. He was also named MVP on defense against Syracuse, Virginia Tech, Cincinnati, and Pitt.\n\n===Senior (2006)===\nIn [[2006 NCAA Division I-A football season|2006]], McLee finally started the whole season. He finished the season with 79 tackles but no sacks. McLee had his second career interception against Connecticut, which he returned for 10 yards. McLee had 9 tackles against [[Marshall University#Athletics|Marshall]], six tackles against Maryland, six against Syracuse, six against Connecticut, six against Cincinnati, and eight tackles in the overtime win against [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]]. McLee finished the season on the [[Butkus Award]] list and traveled to the [[Senior Bowl]].<ref>[http://www.nfl-draft-site.com/2007/01/official-senior-bowl-roster.html The NFL Draft Site: Official Senior Bowl Roster]</ref> In his final game as a Mountaineer, McLee totaled three tackles against [[2006 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football team|Georgia Tech]] in the [[Gator Bowl]].\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Pre-Draft===\nDuring the Senior Bowl, McLee was reported to be \"looking quick\". ESPN ranked McLee as the #14 inside linebacker in the class, out of the 29-ranked inside linebacker prospects. His toughness was praised, while his discipline and learning of schemes were issues. McLee played all three linebacking positions in college, which NFL scouts praised.\n\n===NFL Draft===\nMcLee went undrafted in the [[2007 NFL Draft]]. A day later, McLee signed with the [[St. Louis Rams]], who did not take any linebackers in the draft, as an undrafted free agent. \"It's a slap in the face,\" McLee said. \"Not one of us was drafted. It's very disappointing. We're going to show the league that we can play... They're going to notice us.\" McLee will join with fellow former-Mountaineer and quarterback [[Marc Bulger]].\n\nOn July 18, 2007, McLee's father, Kevin McLee Sr.,<ref name=Kevin /> who was a running back at [[University of Georgia|Georgia]], and former [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Tampa Bay Buccaneer]]<ref name=\"Kevin \"/> died at the age of 52.<ref name=\"McLee Sr.\">{{cite web | url = http://pittsburghlive.com/x/tribunereview/news/fayette/s_517790.html | accessdate = 2008-04-01 | title = Ex-Georgia RB, Uniontown native McLee dies at 52 - Tribune-Review | publisher = PittsburghLIVE.com }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2007, McLee was charged with intent to deliver [[cocaine]] and [[marijuana]] and several traffic violations.<ref>[http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/dailycourier/news/s_552637.html Waives hearing - PittsburghLIVE.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The charges were dropped on February 12, 2008. The charges where however were refiled on February 18.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/dailycourier/news/s_552996.html# |title=Sale of tiger skin |access-date=2008-04-01 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20081016144529/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/dailycourier/news/s_552996.html# |archive-date=2008-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===CFL===\nFollowing being cut by the St. Louis Rams, McLee was signed by the Calgary Stampeders of the [[Canadian Football League]] to a one-year deal. He reported that the [[Green Bay Packers]] were interested in him after his season with Calgary. McLee was later released by Calgary.\n\n===AFL===\nIn 2008, he played in the [[af2]] (a sort of \"farm league\" for the [[Arena Football League]]) with the [[Iowa Barnstormers]] and the [[Green Bay Blizzard]].<ref name=\"'Eers in Pros Profile\">[http://eersinpros.blogspot.com/search/label/Boo%20Mclee 'Eers in Pros Profile]</ref>\n\n===UNGL===\nMclee was drafted into the newly created [[United National Gridiron League]] by [[Team Louisiana]]<ref name=\"'Eers in Pros Profile\"/>\n\n==Personal==\nIn 2016, McLee was charged in a string of bank robberies in [[Pittsburgh]] and [[Crafton, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2016/08/29/former-mountaineers-linebacker-charged-in-string-of-bank-robberies/|title=Former Mountaineers linebacker charged in string of bank robberies|website=[[West Virginia MetroNews]]|date=August 29, 2016|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He pleaded guilty in 2019.<ref name=\"TimesWV\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timeswv.com/sports/former-wvu-linebacker-mclee-dies-at-age-36/article_f69c9368-7d16-11ea-936f-0f8c7c757541.html|title=Former WVU linebacker McLee dies at age 36|first=Bob|last=Hertzel|website=[[Times West Virginian]]|date=April 12, 2020|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMcLee died on April 12, 2020.<ref name=\"TimesWV\"/>\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.msnsportsnet.com/page.cfm?story=8119 Letting It Rip By John Antonik for MSNsportsNET.com August 18, 2005]\n* [http://sports.aol.com/fanhouse/2007/04/30/west-virginia-shut-out-in-the-2007-draft/ West Virginia Shut Out in the 2007 Draft]\n* [http://www.heraldstandard.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=18262714&BRD=2280&PAG=461&dept_id=468632&rfi=6 The Herald Standard - McLee prepared to make that big step to the NFL]\n* [http://www.heraldstandard.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=18278850&BRD=2280&PAG=461&dept_id=468632&rfi=6 The Herald Standard - McLee signed as free agent by Rams]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://insider.espn.go.com/nfldraft/draft/tracker/player?id=10941 Draft tracker] on [[ESPN.com]]\n* [http://eersinpros.blogspot.com/search/label/Boo%20Mclee 'Eers in Pros Profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title=WVU Starting Middle Linebacker| before=[[Grant Wiley]] | after=[[Reed Williams]]|years=2003 - 2006}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McLee, Boo}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Shreveport, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:People from Uniontown, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:West Virginia Mountaineers football players]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Rams players]]\n[[Category:Wheeling Wildcats players]]\n", "name_user": "Skudrafan1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNFL Draft:irrelevant, outdated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boo_McLee"}
