{"title_page": "USS Goodrich (DD-831)", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n|+USS ''Goodrich'' (DD-831)\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= [[File:USS Goodrich (DDR-831) underway at sea in the 1960s.jpg|300px|USS Goodrich (DDR-831)]] \n|Ship caption=''Goodrich'' underway in the 1960s\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States \n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1974}}\n|Ship name=\n|Ship namesake= \n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Bath Iron Works]], [[Bath, Maine]]\n|Ship laid down=18 September 1944\n|Ship launched=25 February 1945\n|Ship sponsor=Mrs. Caspar F. Goodrich\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=24 April 1945\n|Ship decommissioned=30 November 1969\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=1 February 1974\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=*DDR-831, 18 March 1949\n*DD-831, 1 January 1969\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname= \n|Ship honors=\n|Ship fate=Sold for scrap, 12 September 1977\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Gearing|destroyer}}\n|Ship displacement={{convert|3460|LT|t|0|abbr=on}} full\n|Ship length={{convert|390|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|40|ft|10|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|14|ft|4|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship propulsion=Geared turbines, 2 shafts, {{convert|60000|shp|MW|0|abbr=on}}\n|Ship speed={{convert|35|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range={{convert|4500|nmi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|20|kn|abbr=on}}\n|Ship complement=336\n|Ship armament=*6 \u00d7 [[5\"/38 caliber gun]]s\n*12 \u00d7 [[Bofors 40 mm|40 mm AA guns]]\n*11 \u00d7 [[Oerlikon 20 mm cannon|20 mm AA guns]]\n*10 \u00d7 [[American 21 inch torpedo|21 inch (533 mm)]] [[torpedo tube]]s\n*6 \u00d7 [[depth charge]] projectors\n*2 \u00d7 depth charge tracks\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''USS ''Goodrich'' (DD/DDR-831)''' was a {{sclass-|Gearing|destroyer}} of the [[United States Navy]], named for Rear Admiral [[Caspar F. Goodrich]] (1847\u20131925), and his son, Lieutenant [[Caspar Goodrich]] (died 1907).\n\n''Goodrich'' was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 25 February 1945 by the [[Bath Iron Works]] Co., [[Bath, Maine]]; sponsored by Mrs. Caspar F. Goodrich, widow of Admiral Goodrich and mother of Lt. Goodrich; and [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 24 April 1945, Commander Dale R. Frakes in command.\n\n==Service history==\nAfter shakedown training in the [[Caribbean]], ''Goodrich'' transited the [[Panama Canal]] on 12 November 1945 to support the [[occupation of Japan]]. She patrolled between principal [[Japan]]ese ports until October 1946; then she based at [[Qingdao|Tsingtao]], [[China]], for patrol along the coast of [[Korea]]. The destroyer returned to [[San Francisco]], [[California]], on 21 December 1946 and departed on 7 January 1947 to base at [[Naval Station Newport|Newport, Rhode Island]], as a unit of the [[United States Atlantic Fleet]].\n\n''Goodrich'' overhauled in the [[New York Naval Shipyard]], then served in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] (2 February - 22 May 1948). This was her first of many annual tours with the \"steel gray stabilizers\" of the [[United States Sixth Fleet|6th Fleet]], of actively countering the repeated threats of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]s to overrun the defenseless nations of the [[Balkans]] and the [[Middle East]].\n\n''Goodrich'' was reclassified a [[radar picket]] destroyer, DDR-831, on 18 March 1949.\n\n[[File:USS Goodrich (DD-831) underway in 1945.jpg|thumb|left|''Goodrich'' in 1945.]]\n\nHer service included patrol along the [[Israel]]i-[[Egypt]]ian border of the [[Red Sea]] in February 1956 to help stem the [[Suez Crisis|Mid-East crisis]] that finally culminated in the nationalization of the [[Suez Canal]]. When fighting erupted, she sped back to the Mediterranean in November 1956 to protect Americans in that area and serve notice that the United States was determined to contain and terminate the conflict. The destroyer supported the landing of [[1958 Lebanon crisis|Marines at Beirut]], [[Lebanon]], on 14 July 1958, as the Navy again met and checked a [[Communist]] thrust against the Western democracies.\n\n''Goodrich'' shifted her home port in June 1959 from Newport to [[Naval Station Mayport|Mayport, Florida]]. Thereafter her annual deployments to the Mediterranean included intensive training in all forms of naval welfare with [[NATO]] units and a constant readiness with the 6th Fleet to meet any threat to peace in the Mediterranean region. She interrupted her schedule in January 1960, entering the [[Norfolk Navy Yard]] for an eight-month modernization overhaul (FRAM II) which included complete renovation and latest weapons and shipboard equipment. She was on [[Project Mercury]] recovery station on 12 February 1962 as Lieutenant Colonel [[John H. Glenn]], USMC, made his successful [[Friendship 7|orbital space flight]].\n\n''Goodrich'' went on alert again with the 6th Fleet during 24 October to 20 November 1962 when the Navy responded to President [[John F. Kennedy]]'s call for a [[Cuban missile crisis|quarantine of Cuba]] that choked off the flow of military supplies and enforced the American demands for the withdrawal of the Soviet missile experts and equipment. On 22 July 1966 the destroyer got underway from Mayport on her 13th 6th Fleet deployment. She cruised throughout the Mediterranean for five months, unobtrusively patrolling with the 6th Fleet and taking part in combined naval warfare exercises with units of the [[Turkish Navy|Turkish]], [[Hellenic Navy|Greek]], [[Royal Navy|British]], and [[Italian Navy|Italian Navies]]. She returned to Mayport on 20 December 1966 for upkeep and type training.\n\n''Goodrich'' was reclassified DD-831 on 1 January 1969, and was decommissioned on 30 November 1969. Berthed at Orange, Texas, ''Goodrich'' was struck from the [[Naval Vessel Register]] on 1 February 1974. She was sold on 12 September 1977, and broken up for scrap.\n\n== References ==\n{{DANFS|https://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/g/goodrich.html|http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/destroy/dd831txt.htm}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|USS Goodrich (DD-831)}}\n* {{navsource|05/831|USS Goodrich}}\n\n{{Gearing class destroyer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goodrich (DD-831)}}\n[[Category:World War II destroyers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Cold War destroyers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Bath, Maine]]\n[[Category:1945 ships]]\n[[Category:Gearing-class destroyers of the United States Navy]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n|+USS ''Goodrich'' (DD-831)\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= [[File:USS Goodrich (DDR-831) underway at sea in the 1960s.jpg|300px|USS Goodrich (DDR-831)]] \n|Ship caption=''Goodrich'' underway in the 1960s\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States \n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1974}}\n|Ship name=\n|Ship namesake= \n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Bath Iron Works]], [[Bath, Maine]]\n|Ship laid down=18 September 1944\n|Ship launched=25 February 1945\n|Ship sponsor=Mrs. Caspar F. Goodrich\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=24 April 1945\n|Ship decommissioned=30 November 1969\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=1 February 1974\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=*DDR-831, 18 March 1949\n*DD-831, 1 January 1969\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname= \n|Ship honors=\n|Ship fate=Sold for scrap, 12 September 1977\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Gearing|destroyer}}\n|Ship displacement={{convert|3460|LT|t|0|abbr=on}} full\n|Ship length={{convert|390|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|40|ft|10|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|14|ft|4|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship propulsion=Geared turbines, 2 shafts, {{convert|60000|shp|MW|0|abbr=on}}\n|Ship speed={{convert|35|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range={{convert|4500|nmi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|20|kn|abbr=on}}\n|Ship complement=336\n|Ship armament=*6 \u00d7 [[5\"/38 caliber gun]]s\n*12 \u00d7 [[Bofors 40 mm|40 mm AA guns]]\n*11 \u00d7 [[Oerlikon 20 mm cannon|20 mm AA guns]]\n*10 \u00d7 [[American 21 inch torpedo|21 inch (533 mm)]] [[torpedo tube]]s\n*6 \u00d7 [[depth charge]] projectors\n*2 \u00d7 depth charge tracks\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''USS ''Goodrich'' (DD/DDR-831)''' was a {{sclass-|Gearing|destroyer}} of the [[United States Navy]], named for Rear Admiral [[Caspar F. Goodrich]] (1847\u20131925), and his son, Lieutenant [[Caspar Goodrich]] (Died 1907).\n\n''Goodrich'' was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 25 February 1945 by the [[Bath Iron Works]] Co., [[Bath, Maine]]; sponsored by Mrs. Caspar F. Goodrich, widow of Admiral Goodrich and mother of Lt. Goodrich; and [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 24 April 1945, Commander Dale R. Frakes in command.\n\n==Service history==\nAfter shakedown training in the [[Caribbean]], ''Goodrich'' transited the [[Panama Canal]] on 12 November 1945 to support the [[occupation of Japan]]. She patrolled between principal [[Japan]]ese ports until October 1946; then she based at [[Qingdao|Tsingtao]], [[China]], for patrol along the coast of [[Korea]]. The destroyer returned to [[San Francisco]], [[California]], on 21 December 1946 and departed on 7 January 1947 to base at [[Naval Station Newport|Newport, Rhode Island]], as a unit of the [[United States Atlantic Fleet]].\n\n''Goodrich'' overhauled in the [[New York Naval Shipyard]], then served in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] (2 February - 22 May 1948). This was her first of many annual tours with the \"steel gray stabilizers\" of the [[United States Sixth Fleet|6th Fleet]], of actively countering the repeated threats of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]s to overrun the defenseless nations of the [[Balkans]] and the [[Middle East]].\n\n''Goodrich'' was reclassified a [[radar picket]] destroyer, DDR-831, on 18 March 1949.\n\n[[File:USS Goodrich (DD-831) underway in 1945.jpg|thumb|left|''Goodrich'' in 1945.]]\n\nHer service included patrol along the [[Israel]]i-[[Egypt]]ian border of the [[Red Sea]] in February 1956 to help stem the [[Suez Crisis|Mid-East crisis]] that finally culminated in the nationalization of the [[Suez Canal]]. When fighting erupted, she sped back to the Mediterranean in November 1956 to protect Americans in that area and serve notice that the United States was determined to contain and terminate the conflict. The destroyer supported the landing of [[1958 Lebanon crisis|Marines at Beirut]], [[Lebanon]], on 14 July 1958, as the Navy again met and checked a [[Communist]] thrust against the Western democracies.\n\n''Goodrich'' shifted her home port in June 1959 from Newport to [[Naval Station Mayport|Mayport, Florida]]. Thereafter her annual deployments to the Mediterranean included intensive training in all forms of naval welfare with [[NATO]] units and a constant readiness with the 6th Fleet to meet any threat to peace in the Mediterranean region. She interrupted her schedule in January 1960, entering the [[Norfolk Navy Yard]] for an eight-month modernization overhaul (FRAM II) which included complete renovation and latest weapons and shipboard equipment. She was on [[Project Mercury]] recovery station on 12 February 1962 as Lieutenant Colonel [[John H. Glenn]], USMC, made his successful [[Friendship 7|orbital space flight]].\n\n''Goodrich'' went on alert again with the 6th Fleet during 24 October to 20 November 1962 when the Navy responded to President [[John F. Kennedy]]'s call for a [[Cuban missile crisis|quarantine of Cuba]] that choked off the flow of military supplies and enforced the American demands for the withdrawal of the Soviet missile experts and equipment. On 22 July 1966 the destroyer got underway from Mayport on her 13th 6th Fleet deployment. She cruised throughout the Mediterranean for five months, unobtrusively patrolling with the 6th Fleet and taking part in combined naval warfare exercises with units of the [[Turkish Navy|Turkish]], [[Hellenic Navy|Greek]], [[Royal Navy|British]], and [[Italian Navy|Italian Navies]]. She returned to Mayport on 20 December 1966 for upkeep and type training.\n\n''Goodrich'' was reclassified DD-831 on 1 January 1969, and was decommissioned on 30 November 1969. Berthed at Orange, Texas, ''Goodrich'' was struck from the [[Naval Vessel Register]] on 1 February 1974. She was sold on 12 September 1977, and broken up for scrap.\n\n== References ==\n{{DANFS|https://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/g/goodrich.html|http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/destroy/dd831txt.htm}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|USS Goodrich (DD-831)}}\n* {{navsource|05/831|USS Goodrich}}\n\n{{Gearing class destroyer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goodrich (DD-831)}}\n[[Category:World War II destroyers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Cold War destroyers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Bath, Maine]]\n[[Category:1945 ships]]\n[[Category:Gearing-class destroyers of the United States Navy]]\n", "name_user": "Eddie891", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USS_Goodrich_(DD-831)"}
{"title_page": "Behind the Planet of the Apes", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2016}}\n\n'''''Behind the Planet of the Apes''''' is a 1998 American television [[documentary]] directed by Kevin Burns and David Comtois who also co-wrote it with Brian Anthony and produced by [[Foxstar Productions]].\n\n==Premise==\nIt focuses on the five films in the original ''[[Planet of the Apes]]'' series, and is hosted and narrated by [[Roddy McDowall]], who played Cornelius in the 1968 film ''[[Planet of the Apes (film)|Planet of the Apes]]'' and ''[[Escape from the Planet of the Apes]]'' and his son Caesar in ''[[Conquest of the Planet of the Apes]]'' and ''[[Battle for the Planet of the Apes]]''. The documentary premiered on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] to commemorate the thirtieth anniversary of the first 1968 film.<ref name=\"Greene1998\">{{cite book|author=Eric Greene|title=*Planet of the Apes* as American Myth: Race, Politics, and Popular Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZyIiApfhWngC&pg=PR15|year=1998|publisher=Wesleyan University Press|isbn=978-0-8195-6329-3|chapter=preface}}</ref>\n\nThe documentary discusses the ideas and works that led to the production of the films and franchise, including two television series, one live action and one animated series for children. The documentary begins with the [[Planet of the Apes (novel)|original novel]] written by author [[Pierre Boulle]] and how it caught the interest of producer [[Arthur P. Jacobs]], who brought it to [[20th Century Fox]]. The development and production of each film is discussed, including casting, costume design, filming locations and behind the scenes footage.<ref name=\"Hofstede2001\">{{cite book|author=David Hofstede|title=Planet of the Apes: An Unofficial Companion|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OUZ1T4JwMhQC&pg=PA40|year=2001|publisher=ECW Press|isbn=978-1-55022-446-7|pages=40\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nAs of the 2005 [[DVD]] release of all five of the classic films, the documentary was also included in the DVD box set.<ref name=\"Pratt2005\">{{cite book|author=Douglas Pratt|title=Doug Pratt's DVD: Movies, Television, Music, Art, Adult, and More!|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vxmg-LuBTWIC&pg=PA934|year=2005|publisher=UNET 2 Corporation|isbn=978-1-932916-01-0|pages=934\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0207332}}\n\n{{Planet of the Apes}}\n\n[[Category:1998 films]]\n[[Category:1998 television films]]\n[[Category:1990s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about films]]\n[[Category:Planet of the Apes]]\n\n{{documentary-tv-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2016}}\n\n'''''Behind the Planet of the Apes''''' is a 1998 American television [[documentary]] directed by Kevin Burns and David Comtois who also co-wrote it with Brian Anthony and produced by [[Foxstar Productions]].\n\n==Premise==\nIt focuses on the five films in the original ''[[Planet of the Apes]]'' series, and is hosted and narrated by [[Roddy McDowall]], who played Cornelius in the 1968 film ''[[Planet of the Apes (film)|Planet of the Apes]]'' and ''[[Escape from the Planet of the Apes]]'' and his son Caesar in ''[[Conquest of the Planet of the Apes]]'' and ''[[Battle for the Planet of the Apes]]''. The documentary premiered on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] to commemorate the thirtieth anniversary of the first 1968 film.<ref name=\"Greene1998\">{{cite book|author=Eric Greene|title=*Planet of the Apes* as American Myth: Race, Politics, and Popular Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZyIiApfhWngC&pg=PR15|year=1998|publisher=Wesleyan University Press|isbn=978-0-8195-6329-3|chapter=preface}}</ref>\n\nThe documentary discusses the ideas and works that led to the production of the films and franchise, including two television series, one live action and one animated series for children. The documentary begins with the [[Planet of the Apes (novel)|original novel]] written by author [[Pierre Boulle]] and how it caught the interest of producer [[Arthur P. Jacobs]], who brought it to [[20th Century Fox]]. The development and production of each film is discussed, including casting, costume design, filming locations and behind the scenes footage.<ref name=\"Hofstede2001\">{{cite book|author=David Hofstede|title=Planet of the Apes: An Unofficial Companion|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OUZ1T4JwMhQC&pg=PA40|year=2001|publisher=ECW Press|isbn=978-1-55022-446-7|pages=40\u2013}}</ref>\n\nAs of the 2005 [[DVD]] release of all five of the classic films, the documentary was also included in the DVD box set.<ref name=\"Pratt2005\">{{cite book|author=Douglas Pratt|title=Doug Pratt's DVD: Movies, Television, Music, Art, Adult, and More!|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vxmg-LuBTWIC&pg=PA934|year=2005|publisher=UNET 2 Corporation|isbn=978-1-932916-01-0|pages=934\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0207332}}\n\n{{Planet of the Apes}}\n\n[[Category:1998 films]]\n[[Category:1998 television films]]\n[[Category:1990s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about films]]\n[[Category:Planet of the Apes]]\n\n{{documentary-tv-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ARZ100", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Behind_the_Planet_of_the_Apes"}
{"title_page": "Lukas Kampa", "text_new": "{{short description|German volleyball player}}\n{{Infobox volleyball player\n| name             = Lukas Kampa\n| image            = Lukas Kampa - Perugia-Modena 2013-2014.JPG\n| imagesize        = \n| fullname         = Lukas Immanuel Kampa\n| nationality      = {{flagicon|GER}} [[Germany|German]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1986|11|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bochum]], [[Germany]]\n| position         = Setter\n| height           = 1.93 m\n| weight           = 90 kg\n| spike            = 340 cm\n| block            = \n| team             = {{flagicon|POL}} [[Jastrz\u0119bski W\u0119giel]]\n| currentnumber    = 10\n| nationalteam     = {{flagicon|GER}} [[Germany men's national volleyball team|Germany]]\n| nationalyears    = 2008\u2013\n| years            = 2006\u20132008<br>2008\u20132010<br>2010\u20132011<br>2011\u20132012<br>2012\u20132013<br>2013\u20132014<br>2013\u20132014<br>2014\u20132016<br>2016\u2013\n| clubs            = {{flagicon|GER}} Moerser SC<br> {{flagicon|GER}} [[VfB Friedrichshafen]]<br> {{flagicon|GER}} TSV Grafing<br> {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Pallavolo Piacenza|Copra Elior Piacenza]]<br> {{flagicon|RUS}} [[VC Belogorie|Belogorie Belgorod]]<br> {{flagicon|UKR}} [[VC Lokomotyv Kharkiv]]<br> {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Pallavolo Modena|Casa Modena]]<br> {{flagicon|POL}} [[Czarni Radom|Cerrad Czarni Radom]]<br> {{flagicon|POL}} [[Jastrz\u0119bski W\u0119giel]]\n| medaltemplates   =\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[volleyball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{GER}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|World Championship]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2014 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|2014 Poland]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Men's European Volleyball Championship|European Championship]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2017 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2017 Poland]]|}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[European Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2015 European Games|2015 Baku]]|[[Volleyball at the 2015 European Games \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n}}\n'''Lukas Immanuel Kampa''' (born 29 November 1986) is a German [[volleyball]] player, a member of [[Germany men's national volleyball team]] and Polish club [[Jastrz\u0119bski W\u0119giel]], a bronze medalist of the [[2014 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|World Championship 2014]] and named Best Setter of the tournament.\n\n==Personal life==\nKampa was born in [[Bochum]], [[Germany]] as son of Ulrich Kampa - a former [[volleyball]] player. He has a sister and a brother David, who is also a [[volleyball player]].\n\n[[File:Lukas Kampa 2014-15 season.jpeg|thumb|Kampa as the [[Czarni Radom|Cerrad Czarni Radom]] player in season 2014/2015.]]\n\n==Career==\nFor the Germany national team, he had a very good tournament in the 2012 Olympic Qualification tournament. In 2012/13 he was part of a dynamic duo with Georg Grozer in Belgorod and became a Russian Cup winner. In 2014 he signed a contract with Polish club [[Czarni Radom|Cerrad Czarni Radom]].<ref>[http://www.echodnia.eu/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20140926/SPORT04/140929209 ''Lukas Kampa i Dirk Westphal do\u0142\u0105czyli do siatkarzy Cerrad Czarni Radom''] \u2013 echodnia.eu \u2013 26-09-2014</ref>\n\n==Sporting achievements==\n* '''National championships'''\n** '''2008/2009''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Deutsche Volleyball-Bundesliga|German Championship]], with [[VfB Friedrichshafen]]\n** '''2009/2010''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Deutsche Volleyball-Bundesliga|German Championship]], with [[VfB Friedrichshafen]]\n** '''2012/2013''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Russian Cup, with [[VC Belogorie|Belogorie Belgorod]]\n** '''2012/2013''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Russian Volleyball Super League|Russian Championship]], with [[VC Belogorie|Belogorie Belgorod]]\n** '''2013/2014''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Ukrainian Cup, with [[VC Lokomotyv Kharkiv]]\n** '''2013/2014''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Ukrainian Men's Volleyball Super League|Ukrainian Championship]], with [[VC Lokomotyv Kharkiv]]\n** '''2016/2017''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2016\u201317 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Jastrz\u0119bski W\u0119giel]]\n** '''2018/2019''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2018\u201319 PlusLiga|Polish Championship]], with [[Jastrz\u0119bski W\u0119giel]]\n\n* '''National team'''\n** '''2014''' [[File:Bronze medal world centered-2.svg|16px]] [[2014 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|FIVB World Championship]]\n** '''2015''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Volleyball at the 2015 European Games \u2013 Men's tournament|European Games]]\n** '''2017''' [[File:Silver medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2017 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]]\n\n===Individually===\n* '''2014:''' [[2014 FIVB Men's World Championship|FIVB World Championship]] \u2013 Best Setter\n* '''2015:''' [[German Volleyball Player of the Year]]\n* '''2020:''' [[Volleyball at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's European qualification|European qualification for Summer Olympics]] \u2013 Best Setter\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fivb.org/EN/volleyball/competitions/WorldLeague/2014/Players.asp?Tourn=WL2014-2&Team=GER&No=116575 FIVB profile]\n*[http://www.legavolley.it/DettaglioAtleta.asp?IdAtleta=Kam-Luk-86 LegaVolley Serie A player profile]\n*[http://www.plusliga.pl/players/id/26823/Kampa-Lucas/ PlusLiga player profile]\n\n{{commons}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box |\n  | before = {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Nikola Grbi\u0107]]\n  | after = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Micah Christenson]]\n  | title = Best Setter of <br>[[FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|FIVB World Championship]]\n  | years = [[2014 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|2014]]\n|}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kampa, Lukas}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bochum]]\n[[Category:German men's volleyball players]